<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=+2>ESSENTIAL BACKGROUND</FONT></B></CENTER>

<CENTER>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></CENTER>

<br>
<CENTER></CENTER>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1>ON-DEMAND SERVICE TYPES</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=+1></FONT>

<P><FONT SIZE=+1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1. Pay-Per-View (PPV) Service</FONT>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>simplest type, analogous to existing PPV channels</FONT></LI>

<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>time of access for multimedia documents is decided by the
server rather than the client</FONT></LI>

<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>the server multicasts the program at fixed times and any
interested clients tune in to the server at these fixed times</FONT></LI>
</UL>
&nbsp;</UL>
<FONT SIZE=+1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2. Near Video-on-Demand (NVD)
(<a href="c10afig/f10-4.JPG">fig. 10-4</a>)</FONT>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>sometimes called: <b> Shared Viewing with
Constraints</b></FONT></LI> 

<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>motivation: observation that for certain applications, such
as on-demand movies, request arrivals exhibit significant temporal and
spatial locality</FONT></LI>

<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>the client accesses the multimedia documents at any time
it decides by sending a request to the MOD server. The server processes
and accepts these requests in groups to exploit any clustering properties</FONT></LI>

<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>the client can face admission latency after which it becomes
part of a group, all members of which are using the same connection</FONT></LI>

<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1><I>advantage</I>: the client can access data at any time
instance</FONT></LI>

<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1><I>disadvantage</I>: difficult to implement for applications
that
don't exhibit clustering properties</FONT></LI>
</UL>
&nbsp;</UL>
<FONT SIZE=+1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3. True Multimedia-On-Demand
(TMOD)</FONT>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>each access request from clients is treated independently
at the server</FONT></LI>

<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1><I>advantage</I>: personalized, interactive multimedia
delivery</FONT></LI>

<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1><I>disadvantage</I>: serious implications in
throughput</FONT></LI>
</UL>
</UL>
<FONT SIZE=+1></FONT>&nbsp;
